latestPosts.caption:
I am originally from Kazakhstan 🇰🇿 — a land of endless steppes, majestic mountains, and truly warm-hearted people.
It’s a place where every morning feels wide open and free, and every person welcomes you with a sincere soul.
Kazakhstan is not only the homeland of my heart, but also a country where cosmetology is flourishing at a high level, combining modern techniques with genuine Eastern care.

Traditional hair braiding is part of our cultural identity — a beautiful expression of heritage and style.
That’s why I’ve included Kazakh-inspired braiding techniques in my hair program, blending tradition with professional education.
I’m proud of my roots and carry this strength and beauty into my work here in America 🇺🇸

The past few months brought me two relocations.
Change often means growth, but sometimes it’s painfully hard.

The first move was challenging:
New walls, new rules, new worries for my team and students.
For some, “comfort” meant pretty views and fancy chairs,
while we struggled with basic things like air to breathe.
We couldn’t even adjust the AC —
feeling like fish out of water, suffocating and unheard.

Then came the second move.
Unexpected. Stressful.
It felt like the ground was slipping away.
The place I built with love turned into a battle.
Not everything we create turns out perfect — and that’s okay.

This experience taught me to face my fears,
to stay flexible, brave, and most importantly —
to stay true to myself.

Sometimes failure is not a fall,
but a sign to take a better path.

If you’re going through changes too —
don’t be afraid to feel tired, angry, disappointed.
That’s human.
Your strength is in your authenticity,
not in perfect conditions.
You create the atmosphere, not the walls.

Today I’m grateful:
For the lessons, for my team, for my students,
and for myself — for not giving
